to go to the bathroom.

58
00:04:51,625 --> 00:04:55,628
You go and say hello, and I'll
meet you where? At the bar?

59
00:04:56,130 --> 00:04:57,213
Good.

60
00:05:07,641 --> 00:05:09,100
BILL:
Nightingale.

61
00:05:09,935 --> 00:05:11,102
Nick Nightingale!

62
00:05:11,353 --> 00:05:13,605
Oh, my God! Bill.

63
00:05:14,106 --> 00:05:17,025
Bill Harford!
How the hell are you, buddy?

64
00:05:17,234 --> 00:05:20,653
- How long has it been?
- I don't know. Ten years?

65
00:05:20,863 --> 00:05:22,197
And a couple.

66
00:05:22,781 --> 00:05:24,616
- Do you have time for a drink?
- Sure.

67
00:05:28,746 --> 00:05:30,872
You haven't changed a bit.

68
00:05:31,081 --> 00:05:33,958
Thanks, I think.
So how you doing?

69
00:05:34,210 --> 00:05:36,878
Not too bad, you know. Not too bad.

70
00:05:37,087 --> 00:05:39,380
I see you've become a pianist.

71
00:05:39,590 --> 00:05:42,133
Oh, yes, well, my friends call me that.

72
00:05:43,052 --> 00:05:45,595
How about you?
You still in the doctor business?

73
00:05:45,804 --> 00:05:49,849
You know what they say:
"Once a doctor, always a doctor. "

74
00:05:50,059 --> 00:05:54,354
Yes, or in my case:
"Never a doctor, never a doctor. "

75
00:05:55,189 --> 00:05:57,607
I never did understand
why you walked away.

76
00:05:58,359 --> 00:06:00,693
It's a nice feeling. I do it a lot.

77
00:06:00,903 --> 00:06:02,111
Cheers.

78
00:06:02,696 --> 00:06:06,115
Excuse me.
Nick, I need you a minute.

79
00:06:06,325 --> 00:06:07,951
Be right with you.

80
00:06:08,160 --> 00:06:10,828
I gotta go do something.
If I don't catch you later...

81
00:06:11,038 --> 00:06:14,832
...I'll be down at the Village
for two weeks at the Sonata Café.

82
00:06:15,042 --> 00:06:17,710
- Stop by if you get a chance.
- I'll be there.

83
00:06:18,546 --> 00:06:21,506
- It's great seeing you.
- Good seeing you too, man.

84
00:07:03,007 --> 00:07:06,426
I think that's my glass.

85
00:07:06,635 --> 00:07:09,762
I'm absolutely certain of it.

86
00:07:23,777 --> 00:07:27,780
My name is Sandor Szavost.
I'm Hungarian.

87
00:07:38,417 --> 00:07:40,835
My name is Alice Harford.

88
00:07:41,170 --> 00:07:43,212
I'm American.

89
00:07:43,881 --> 00:07:45,798
Delighted to meet you, Alice.

90
00:07:47,384 --> 00:07:52,138
Did you ever read the Latin poet Ovid
on The Art of Love?

91
00:07:54,266 --> 00:07:57,894
Didn't he wind up all by himself...

92
00:07:58,520 --> 00:08:00,855
...crying his eyes out...

93
00:08:01,065 --> 00:08:04,817
...in some place
with a very bad climate?

94
00:08:06,028 --> 00:08:08,946
But he also had a good time first.

95
00:08:09,406 --> 00:08:11,741
A very good time.

96
00:08:14,203 --> 00:08:16,996
Are you here
with anyone tonight, Alice?

97
00:08:20,125 --> 00:08:22,168
With my husband.

98
00:08:22,503 --> 00:08:24,462
Oh, how sad.

99
00:08:25,172 --> 00:08:30,093
But then I'm sure he's the sort of man
who wouldn't mind if we danced.

100
00:08:34,932 --> 00:08:37,141
What do you do, Alice?

101
00:08:37,685 --> 00:08:41,062
Well, at the moment...

102
00:08:41,855 --> 00:08:44,232
...I'm looking for a job.

103
00:08:45,401 --> 00:08:49,153
I used to manage
an art gallery in SoHo.

104
00:08:49,822 --> 00:08:51,948
But it went broke.

105
00:08:54,034 --> 00:08:55,576
What a shame.

106
00:08:57,287 --> 00:08:59,831
I have some friends in the art game.

107
00:09:00,499 --> 00:09:02,709
Perhaps I can be of some help.

108
00:09:06,463 --> 00:09:08,131
Thank you.

109
00:09:27,317 --> 00:09:28,943
Someone you know?

110
00:09:32,823 --> 00:09:34,490
My...

111
00:09:35,033 --> 00:09:36,576
...husband.

112
00:09:36,827 --> 00:09:37,952
Oh.

113
00:09:41,248 --> 00:09:44,292
Don't you think
one of the charms of marriage...

114
00:09:44,543 --> 00:09:49,172
...is that it makes deception
a necessity for both parties?

115
00:09:53,093 --> 00:09:55,678
May I ask why a beautiful woman...

116
00:09:56,180 --> 00:09:59,849
...who could have any man in this room,
wants to be married?

117
00:10:02,811 --> 00:10:04,812
Why wouldn't she?

118
00:10:06,607 --> 00:10:08,691
Is it as bad as that?

119
00:10:09,985 --> 00:10:12,361
As good as that.

120
00:10:13,113 --> 00:10:14,864
Do you know Nuala Windsor?

121
00:10:15,073 --> 00:10:19,702
No, and it's very lovely
to meet you both.

122
00:10:21,705 --> 00:10:23,748
How do you spell Nuala?

123
00:10:24,374 --> 00:10:29,295
N- U-A-L-A.

124
00:10:31,048 --> 00:10:33,800
You don't remember me, do you?

125
00:10:34,968 --> 00:10:37,553
You were very kind to me once.

126
00:10:37,763 --> 00:10:41,516
Only once?
That sounds like a terrible oversight!

127
00:10:42,893 --> 00:10:47,104
I was doing a photo session
in Rockefeller Plaza...

128
00:10:47,314 --> 00:10:48,898
...on a very windy day...?

129
00:10:49,107 --> 00:10:53,319
- And you got something in your eye.
- Just about half of Fifth Avenue.

130
00:10:53,737 --> 00:10:57,240
You were such a gentleman!
You gave me your handkerchief...

131
00:10:57,491 --> 00:10:59,951
...which was also clean.

132
00:11:01,620 --> 00:11:05,331
That is the kind of hero
I can be sometimes.

133
00:11:06,291 --> 00:11:09,418
You know why women used to get married,
don't you?

134
00:11:10,963 --> 00:11:13,172
Why don't you tell me?

135
00:11:14,925 --> 00:11:17,885
It was the only way they could
lose their virginity...

136
00:11:18,303 --> 00:11:21,889
...and be free to do
what they wanted with other men.

137
00:11:22,933 --> 00:11:25,142
The ones they really wanted.

138
00:11:29,815 --> 00:11:31,816
Fascinating.

139
00:11:35,779 --> 00:11:39,532
Do you know what's so nice
about doctors?

140
00:11:41,159 --> 00:11:44,662
Usually a lot less than people imagine.

141
00:11:46,373 --> 00:11:49,000
They always seem so...

142
00:11:49,918 --> 00:11:51,460
...knowledgeable.

143
00:11:52,462 --> 00:11:56,299
Oh, they are very knowledgeable...

144
00:11:56,508 --> 00:11:59,385
...about all sorts of things.

145
00:12:01,346 --> 00:12:03,472
But I bet they work too hard.

146
00:12:03,974 --> 00:12:07,768
Just think of all they miss.

147
00:12:08,687 --> 00:12:11,022
You're probably right.

148
00:12:12,024 --> 00:12:16,819
Ladies, where exactly are we going?

149
00:12:17,487 --> 00:12:19,030
Exactly?

150
00:12:21,491 --> 00:12:24,035
Where the rainbow ends.

151
00:12:24,620 --> 00:12:26,495
Where the rainbow ends?

152
00:12:26,705 --> 00:12:30,166
Don't you want to go
where the rainbow ends?

153
00:12:30,375 --> 00:12:33,461
Now that depends where that is.

154
00:12:33,670 --> 00:12:35,338
Well, let's find out.

155
00:12:35,547 --> 00:12:38,382
Excuse me, ladies.
Sorry, Dr. Harford.

156
00:12:38,634 --> 00:12:42,887
Could you come with me for a moment?
Something for Mr. Ziegler.

157
00:12:45,223 --> 00:12:46,390
Fine.

158
00:12:48,143 --> 00:12:49,560
To be continued?

159
00:13:07,204 --> 00:13:08,371
